Incarceration rate in the US

Trang Tran

02/25/2022

Summary

The unjust mass incarceration of the US that backed a massive prison industrial complex masks under political righteousness of the war on drugs to uphold the systemic racism. When the systems core focus is not on the safety of the people and the greater good of society, but on the benefits of the powerful and wealthy few, the reality is unsettling. According to the documentation The 13th, the US accounts for only 5% of the worlds population but 25% of the worlds prison population. One in four of the people that are locked-up is in America, the land of the free and the symbol of democracy. This statistic urges the questions of why and what has really been happening?

The current project

In an effort of investigating what the picture of incarceration in the US looks like, this project uses the jail and prison population data set from the Vera Institutes for the analysis, which covers the period from 1970 to 2018. Specifically, the focal point rests on how systemic racism ties to the current mass incarceration in the US. Hence, the main variables of interest are the demographics of jail and prison population in terms of racial identity and the corresponding proportion to the general population. The data showed that the average black prison population each year is 2.57731^{5}, while the average white prison population each year is 2.10709^{5}. These numbers would be not alarming, had it not been clear that White people accounts for the majority of the US population, while Black population is the exact opposite. Moreover, the largest prison population in a year is 1.2608786^{6}; the largest prison population over total population in a year is 0.007, which means 7 out of 1000 people were incarcerated.

Trend lines

Here is a graph showcasing prison population of each racial groups over time from 1970 to 2018. I particularly chose this graph because I want to address the question of how the prison population differs across different race in the US. One noteworthy pattern here is that black people make up the majority of the prison population, slightly higher than white prison population, despite being a minority group.

Comparison

Here is a graph expressing the ratio between incarcerated population and total population of Black and White communities over time from 1970 to 2018. From the pattern emerging from the trend line graph above, I want to compare incarceration rate per 100000 people between Black and White population, to have a clearer picture of the disparity in incarceration rate between the two racial group. The graph highlights that Black people are disproportionately incarcerated compared to white people, with a staggering gap.

Map

The incarcerated population and total population ratio is showed geographically within the US in 2018. From the map, we can see the South which has a major history of slavery and racism, generally has higher incarceration rate compared to the rest of the US.
